Document: Compositor
Path: godot/tutorials/rendering/compositor.rst
Summary: Introduces the Compositor feature in Godot 4, explaining its purpose and configuration options.
The compositor is a new feature in Godot 4 that allows control over the rendering pipeline when rendering the contents of a Viewport. It can be configured on a WorldEnvironment node where it applies to all Viewports, or it can be configured on a Camera3D and apply only to the Viewport using that camera. The Compositor resource is used to configure the compositor. To get started, create a new compositor on the appropriate node. Note: The compositor is currently a feature that is only supported by the Mobile and Forward+ renderers.
---CHUNK---
Document: Compositor effects
Path: godot/tutorials/rendering/compositor.rst
Summary: This tutorial explains how to implement custom post-processing effects in Godot using the CompositorEffect class and compute shaders.

Compositor effects allow you to insert custom logic into the rendering pipeline. Because this logic executes within the rendering thread, developers must manage threading carefully to avoid conflicts.

To create a compositor effect, extend the CompositorEffect class. Use a tool script to enable previewing in the editor.

GDScript:
    @tool
    extends CompositorEffect
    class_name PostProcessShader

The effect requires a compute shader. A template string is used to define the boilerplate, including the image binding and push constants. The #COMPUTE_CODE placeholder is replaced by user-defined shader code at runtime.

Use a Mutex to protect data shared between the main thread and the rendering thread, specifically when updating shader code or flags.

Initialization:
In the _init() method, set the effect_callback_type to define when the effect runs. Currently, only 3D rendering pipeline stages are supported. Retrieve the RenderingDevice via RenderingServer.get_rendering_device().

Cleanup:
React to the NOTIFICATION_PREDELETE notification to free the shader RID. The RenderingDevice handles dependency tracking, so the compute pipeline will be freed automatically when the shader is destroyed.

Shader Compilation:
The _check_shader() helper function manages compilation. It checks if the shader is "dirty," replaces the template placeholder with user code, and compiles the GLSL source into SPIR-V using rd.shader_compile_spirv_from_source().

Warning: Compiling shaders at runtime is excellent for prototyping but may prevent precompilation and caching on platforms like consoles. For production, consider using external .glsl files.

Rendering Callback:
The _render_callback() method is called by the rendering thread every frame.
1. Access render buffers via p_render_data.get_render_scene_buffers(), cast to RenderSceneBuffersRD.
2. Calculate group sizes based on the internal render resolution.
3. Populate push constants using a PackedFloat32Array. Note: Data must be 16-byte aligned (array length must be a multiple of 4).
4. Iterate through views to support stereo/multiview rendering.
5. Retrieve the color buffer using get_color_layer(view).
6. Create a uniform set using UniformSetCacheRD to ensure memory safety and efficient caching.
7. Execute the compute shader using rd.compute_list_begin(), bind the pipeline and uniform set, dispatch the work, and end the list.

Integration:
To use the effect, add it to the CompositorEffects array in the Compositor resource. You can then input custom GLSL code into the exported shader_code property to modify the rendered output, such as applying a grayscale filter.

Note: The effect_callback_type check in the render callback is a safety mechanism, as users can modify this property in the inspector.